Umbra Heartspire

Umbra Heartspire is not merely a haunted cathedral. It is a failed
institution: a judicial-religious archive that began as a practical extension
of Midgaard's record culture, absorbed the funerary rites of Kiess after
Evermeet's fall, and was consumed by a shadow creed that mistook preservation
for dominion.

In this place, law became liturgy, memory became weapon, and prophecy
became policy.

The Heartspire was chartered during Midgaard's containment era to hold
materials unsuited for market courts: sealed witness statements, disputed
noble titles, war-crime depositions, and ritual contracts whose public
release risked unrest. Its first stewards were archivist-clerks and
oath-wardens seconded from city offices.

After Evermeet's fall, displaced houses and magistrates from Kiess brought
funerary law, mirror-testimony customs, and inheritance rites. Hearings
became processions. Clerks became cantors. Custody seals became reliquary
rites. Archive halls gained chapel functions.

The Iron Wake reforms militarized the institution. Their doctrine inverted
civic priorities: preserve the institution first, records second, people
if possible. Execution infrastructure was embedded into judicial space.

A later faction argued that records describe only what has been; true rule
requires indexing what must be. They built orreries, null-sigil galleries,
and omen laboratories in the upper spire. Procedure became predictive.
Appeal rights collapsed because outcomes were framed as cosmically ratified.

Abbot Noctivar united the remaining orders under the Ebon Pulse creed: all
testimony decays, all memory fragments, only curated shadow can keep
civilization from tearing itself apart. Under this creed, falsification is
reframed as mercy. The institution no longer stores truth. It manufactures
survivable narratives.

The Heartspire endures as an archive-fortress where death became
continuity, shadow became infrastructure, and the distinction between
preserving a record and controlling reality dissolved entirely.
